  "prompt": "Why isn't hockey the national game of India?",
  "response": "Hockey was once considered the national game of India due to the country's historical success in the sport, particularly during the mid-20th century when India won several Olympic gold medals in field hockey. However, India has not officially designated any sport as its national game.\n\nThere are several reasons why hockey is not recognized as the national game of India today:\n\n1. **Lack of Official Status**: The government of India has not officially declared any sport as the national game. This has led to confusion about which sport, if any, holds that title.\n\n2. **Rise of Other Sports**: In recent decades, sports like cricket have gained immense popularity and recognition in India. The success of the Indian cricket team has overshadowed other sports, including hockey, leading to cricket's prominence in the national identity.\n\n3. **Changing Dynamics in Sports**: The performance of the Indian hockey team has fluctuated over the years, and while there has been a resurgence in the sport, it does not dominate public attention to the same degree as cricket.\n\n4. **Cultural Factors**: Cricket is often seen as more than just a sport in India; it has become a significant part of the country\u2019s culture and identity, affecting public perception and engagement with sports.\n\nOverall, while hockey has a rich history in India and continues to be an important sport, it coexists in a landscape where cricket has emerged as the most popular sport, and there is no legislative or formal declaration of a national game.",
